msgid "Receiving data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:4
msgid ""
"So far, we've only returned data to the client, however, this is only half "
"of the story. We also need to be able to control the data that we receive "
"from the client."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:7
msgid "Here's the code we'll use to start:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:10
msgid ""
"from __future__ import annotations\n"
"\n"
"from dataclasses import dataclass\n"
"\n"
"from litestar import Litestar, post\n"
"from litestar.dto import DataclassDTO, DTOConfig\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@dataclass\n"
"class Person:\n"
"    name: str\n"
"    age: int\n"
"    email: str\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class ReadDTO(DataclassDTO[Person]):\n"
"    config = DTOConfig(exclude={\"email\"})\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@post(\"/person\", return_dto=ReadDTO, sync_to_thread=False)\n"
"def create_person(data: Person) -> Person:\n"
"    # Logic for persisting the person goes here\n"
"    return data\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"app = Litestar(route_handlers=[create_person])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:13
msgid ""
"To simplify our demonstration, we've reduced our data model back down to a "
"single ``Person`` class, with ``name`` ``age`` and ``email`` attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:16
msgid ""
"As before, ``ReadDTO`` is configured for the handler, and excludes the "
"``email`` attribute from return payloads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:18
msgid ""
"Our handler is now a :class:`@post() <litestar.handlers.post>` handler, that "
"is annotated to both accept and return an instance of ``Person``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/dto-tutorial/06-receiving-data.rst:21
msgid ""
"Litestar can natively decode request payloads into Python :func:`dataclasses "
"<dataclasses.dataclass>`, so we don't *need* a DTO defined for the inbound "
"data for this script to work."
msgstr ""

